cussions about intersectionality and oppression, the frailty of the human, and the embeddedness of the human being in nature, society, and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aContinental philosophy. 0aHuman beings. 0aHumanism. 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 0aPhilosophy, Germany20th century. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : History of Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh1 aFarin, Ingo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMalpas, Jeff, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849050240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438490502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438490502/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles